song.description_preview:
The opening track to the widely acclaimed Random Access Memories. This song is the fifth single from the album.

This song introduces us to the album by asking us to feel the music, to feel identified with the lyrics. That’s why this album was so meticulously crafted with immaculate production, so we can feel it.
song.full_title: Give Life Back to Music by Daft Punk
song.title: Give Life Back to Music

song.description_preview:
The Chorus here means that walking away is just accepting the love you had for the person and realizing that you should have told them before and not after the relationship.

As Nick Stevenson has described the 

“ ‘The Game of Love’ is a song about lost love that tugs at the heartstrings, even if it is being sung by an android.”
song.full_title: The Game of Love by Daft Punk
song.title: The Game of Love

song.description_preview: Daft Punk uses a monologue by famed Italian producer and dance music pioneer Giorgio Moroder timed with precision over a new beat to describe their process and the essence, evolution and condition of dance music.

song.description_preview:
This is the 2nd song Daft Punk recorded featuring Pharrell off of Daft Punk’s masterful Random Access Memories.

Dancing releases endorphins and reduces stress, in the lyrics Pharrell and Daft Punk tell this individual to take a break from the stress of life and shake the stress away and lose themselves in dance.
song.full_title: Lose Yourself to Dance by Daft Punk (Ft. Pharrell Williams)
song.title: Lose Yourself to Dance
song.title_with_featured: Lose Yourself to Dance (Ft. Pharrell Williams)

song.description_preview:
Featuring vocals from renowned singer-songwriter Paul Williams, this song marks the midpoint of Random Access Memories and seems to possibly continue where “Within” left off.

Opening with a bizarre segment consisting of warped sines and synths, this track takes cues from the work of the late electronic composer Karlheinz Stockhausen before taking listeners on a genre-bending ride that spans electronic, ragtime, and orchestral music.

Paul’s vocals seep in and out of the song, longing for not only the physical, but emotional “touch” of other people after an extended period of time in isolation. The speaker may have had plenty of time to think and reflect while in their lonesome, but after looking inside themselves, they realize that they are missing something, and need “something more” to be fulfilled and feel truly human.
song.full_title: Touch by Daft Punk (Ft. Paul Williams)
song.title: Touch

song.full_title: Get Lucky by Daft Punk (Ft. Nile Rodgers & Pharrell Williams)
song.title: Get Lucky
song.title_with_featured: Get Lucky (Ft. Nile Rodgers & Pharrell Williams)

song.description_preview:
“Beyond” deals with a multitude of various themes which have been recurrent throughout the album. The most straightforward message of the song is to allow and push oneself to simply go “beyond” in life. Go beyond your dreams, go beyond love, lose control and reach for that higher state of being.

This elevated emotional state is subtly compared to that of God, as the human consciousness is what spurns these ideas of love and dreams, and can create an internal world all on it’s own, while also influencing the real world with it’s affects on life and understanding. The world we live in and how understand it is all based on perception, so one’s mind is truly the “end and the beginning” of everything we know and feel.
song.title: Beyond

song.description_preview:
Daft Punk save the good times on their hard drive, make a song out of it, and then play that thing on repeat!!

The song features Todd Edwards on vocals, who already appeared in their second album Discovery, both co-producing and providing vocals on one of the tracks, Face to face.
song.full_title: Fragments of Time by Daft Punk (Ft. Todd Edwards)
song.title: Fragments of Time

song.description_preview: On the 12th track from the Grammy Award winning album, Daft Punk teams up with Panda Bear aka Noah Benjamin Lennox.
song.full_title: Doin' It Right by Daft Punk (Ft. Panda Bear)
song.title: Doin’ It Right

song.description_preview: The closing track on Random Access Memories, raising numerous questions about the existence of intelligent life outside of planet Earth. It makes use of a sampled radio message from Apollo 17; another recording from that mission was used on Public Service Broadcasting’s song “Tomorrow”.
song.title: Contact

song.description_preview: A bonus track from the Japanese version of Daft Punk’s Random Access Memories. The track is entirely instrumental and is much more psychedelic than the rest of the mostly disco-influenced album. The track prominently features a acoustic guitar backed up by multiple synthesizers.
song.title: Horizon

song.description_preview:
“Random Access Memories”is the fourth album of electronic music duo Daft Punk.

A month earlier, the biggest hit as the CD single was  “Get Lucky” with Pharrell Williams. The song reached the top spot of the charts in more than 10 countries.

Other singles in charge of promotion of the album were “Lose Yourself to Dance”, which is more a partnership with Pharrell and “Instant Crush” with Julian Casablancas.

body.html:
Inaninterview with Pitchfork, the group said:

It became clear that we were limited by our own disability to hold a groove the way we wanted for more than eight or 16 bars. Something we love about disco is the idea of playing the same groove over and over again—your brain can tell it’s not a sample that’s being replayed. […] The idea of working with musicians was way beyond making it sound better. It was an opportunity to create something on a very personal level with people that we admire the most. […] That’s how you did it in the old days—when a person is paying you top dollar, you want to make sure that they’re happy and they don’t have to call you back. So I just bombarded them with ideas and said, “OK, now you guys figure that shit out.”
body.markdown:
In an [interview with *Pitchfork*](http://pitchfork.com/features/cover-story/reader/daft-punk/), the group said:

>It became clear that we were limited by our own disability to hold a groove the way we wanted for more than eight or 16 bars. Something we love about disco is the idea of playing the same groove over and over again---your brain can tell it's not a sample that's being replayed. [...] The idea of working with musicians was way beyond making it sound better. It was an opportunity to create something on a very personal level with people that we admire the most. [...] That's how you did it in the old days---when a person is paying you top dollar, you want to make sure that they're happy and they don't have to call you back. So I just bombarded them with ideas and said, "OK, now you guys figure that shit out."
